1. Output Function (print())

• In Python, we use print() to display information on the screen.
• It can show text, numbers, or variable values.


Syntax:

print(value1, value2, ...)

Examples:

print("Hello, World!")        
print(10)                     
x = 5
print("Value of x is:", x)    

Output:  Hello, World!
         10
         Value of x is: 5

2. Input Function (input())

In Python, we use input() to take data from the user.

By default, input is taken as a string.

If you need numbers, you must convert using int() or float().


Syntax:

variable = input("Message for user: ")

Examples:

name = input("Enter your name: ")
print("Hello,", name)

age = int(input("Enter your age: "))   # Converts string to integer
print("You are", age, "years old")

Output (depends on user input):

Enter your name: Alex
Hello, Alex
Enter your age: 21
You are 21 years old


